This paper is about improving the performance of spoken language understanding (SLU) and dialog systems using neural network-based methods. The paper proposes a novel paraphrasing-based SLU model that can handle rare and complex paraphrased utterances. The paper uses RNN and sequence-to-sequence based neural networks, which are commonly used in natural language processing (NLP) and machine learning (ML) research. Therefore, the most likely arXiv CS sub-categories are cs.CL (Computation and Language), cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), and cs.LG (Machine Learning). Additionally, the paper proposes a new model architecture, which involves training a neural network to generate paraphrases of user utterances. This approach is similar to recent work in neural machine translation (NMT), which falls under the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category. Finally, the paper evaluates the proposed models on benchmark datasets, which involves testing the models under different conditions and distributions. This type of evaluation is common in software engineering (SE) and systems research, which falls under the cs.SD (Software Engineering) sub-category.
